    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 4, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🚢 Iran Is Now Eyeing a Second Global Chokepoint\n\nWith Hormuz already closed, Iranian Parliament Speaker Ghalibaf posted a pointed \"rhetorical\" question on social media Saturday: *\"What share of global oil, LNG, wheat, rice, and fertilizer shipments transits the Bab el-Mandeb Strait?\"* He did not answer. He didn't need to.\n\n- **The stakes:** Bab el-Mandeb connects the Red Sea to the Gulf of Aden — the gateway to Suez. 6.2 million barrels/day, ~12% of global trade. The Houthis, who take direction from Tehran, can resume drone and missile attacks almost immediately.\n- **The combined scenario:** Hormuz + Bab el-Mandeb simultaneously = ~30% of global container shipping rerouted, ~22% of global oil supply disrupted. A social media post with a measurable effect on energy futures.\n\n*Hormuz is already closed. Tehran is now pointing at chokepoint number two. Very rhetorical. Very expensive if it isn't.*\n\n**Sources:** [Sunday Guardian Live](https://sundayguardianlive.com/world/us-israel-iran-war-day-36-latest-news-update-iran-eyes-bab-el-mandeb-after-strait-of-hormuz-blockade-top-official-signals-threat-to-global-oil-route-amid-escalating-middle-east-tensions-181270/) | [CBS News](https://www.cbsnews.com/news/iran-strait-of-hormuz-bab-el-mandeb-yemen-houthis/)\n\n---\n\n## ⏰ Trump: 48 Hours to Open Hormuz or \"All Hell Rains Down.\" Iran Said No.\n\nTrump issued a 48-hour ultimatum: reopen the Strait or face escalated strikes. Iran rejected a US ceasefire proposal outright. A US Black Hawk conducting search-and-rescue for the missing airman was also hit by Iranian fire — it stayed airborne. Iran now claims it used \"a new advanced defence system\" to down the aircraft, directly contradicting earlier US claims that Iranian air defences had been destroyed.\n\n- **The ultimatum track record:** US ultimatums in the Middle East have mixed outcomes. This one expires over the weekend. Monday looks complicated.\n- **The defence system discrepancy:** either Iran has operational air defences the US didn't destroy, or US claims were overstated. Both sides can't be right simultaneously. Probably neither is fully right.\n\n*48-hour deadline. Iran said no. At least one party now has to decide what that means.*\n\n**Sources:** [Times of Israel](https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog-april-4-2026/) | [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/04/nx-s1-5773436/iran-war-updates)\n\n---\n\n## 🎂 One Year of Liberation Day Tariffs: The Receipts Are In\n\nApril 2, 2025: Trump announced \"Liberation Day\" tariffs — 34% on China, 20% on the EU, 46% on Vietnam. One year later: the Supreme Court struck down the IEEPA tariffs in February 2026. The trade deficit hit a record in 2025. The scorecard is not what was advertised.\n\n- **The ledger:** 89,000 fewer US manufacturing jobs. $600–$1,000 in extra annual costs per US household. The tariffs were designed to fix the trade deficit. They made it worse.\n- **The structural shift:** partners who built alternate trade routes didn't do it temporarily. The EU, India, the UK signed new deals while Washington focused on tariff arithmetic. A Supreme Court ruling doesn't un-sign those agreements.\n\n*One year. A record trade deficit. A Supreme Court reversal. And the alternate routes are now permanent. Liberation Day liberated something — just not what anyone promised.*\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/04/02/liberation-day-1-year-on-investors-are-rethinking-us-assets.html) | [Axios](https://www.axios.com/2026/04/02/trump-trade-tariffs-liberation-day)"
